Text mining, sentiment analysis, and visualization

created on 22 November 2020 and updated 14 November, 2022

Sentiment Analysis on Hemingway

1. Load the text:

hemingway_path <- here("data","hemingway.pdf")
hemingway_text <- pdf_text(hemingway_path)

2. Data Wranling:

hemingway_df <- data.frame(hemingway_text) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_split(hemingway_text, pattern = '\\n')) %>% 
  unnest(text_full) %>% 
  mutate(text_full = str_trim(text_full)) 

hemingway_tokens <- hemingway_df %>% 
  unnest_tokens(word, text_full)

3. Remove stopwords:

# count words to illustrate the many stopwords
hemingway_tokens_wc <- hemingway_tokens %>% 
  count(word) %>% 
  arrange(-n)

# remove stopwords
hemingway_stop <- hemingway_tokens %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words) %>% 
  select(-hemingway_text)

# look at the beuaty
hemingway_swc <- hemingway_stop %>% 
  count(word) %>% 
  arrange(-n)

# get rid of numbers
hemingway_no_numeric <- hemingway_stop %>% 
  filter(is.na(as.numeric(word)))


word_freq_head <- head(hemingway_tokens_wc)
word_freq_head_2 <- head(hemingway_swc)

Display the most frequent words:

word_freq_head %>% 
    kbl() %>% 
    kable_styling()

Display the most frequent words after removing stopwords:

4. Create Wordcloud

# Extract 100 most frequent words
hemingway_top100 <- hemingway_no_numeric %>% 
  count(word) %>% 
  arrange(-n) %>% 
  head(100)

# create wordcloud
set.seed(1234) # for reproducibility 
wordcloud(words = hemingway_top100$word, freq = hemingway_top100$n, min.freq = 1, max.words=100, random.order=FALSE, rot.per=0.35,colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))

5. Sentiment analysis with AFINN

hemingway_afinn <- hemingway_stop %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn"))

5.1. Plotting distribution of sentiment values

hemingway_afinn %>% 
  ggplot(aes(value))+
  geom_bar(fill="lightblue", width = 0.8)+
  labs(
    title="Distribution of sentiment values",
    subtitle = "A Moveable Fest, Hemingway",
    x="Sentiment value",
    y="Count"
  )+
  theme_minimal()

5.2. Checking out the most frequent positive words

# positive words
# get the positive words
hemingway_pos <- hemingway_afinn %>% 
  filter(value > 1)

# count & plot them
hemingway_pos_10 <- hemingway_pos %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(word = fct_reorder(factor(word), n)) %>% 
  slice(1:10)

ggplot(data = hemingway_pos_10, aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill="pink") +
  coord_flip()+
  labs(
    title="Top 10 positive words",
    subtitle = "A Moveable Fest, Hemingway",
    x="Word",
    y="Count"
  )+
  theme_minimal()

5.3. Checking out the most frequent negative words

# negative words
# get the negative words
hemingway_pos <- hemingway_afinn %>% 
  filter(value < -1)

# count & plot them
hemingway_pos_10 <- hemingway_pos %>% 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  mutate(word = fct_reorder(factor(word), n)) %>% 
  slice(1:10)

ggplot(data = hemingway_pos_10, aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill="darkgreen") +
  coord_flip()+
  labs(
    title="Top 10 negative words",
    subtitle = "A Moveable Fest, Hemingway",
    x="Word",
    y="Count"
  )+
  theme_minimal()

Summarising sentiment

hemingway_summary <- hemingway_afinn %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_score = mean(value),
    median_score = median(value)
  )
hemingway_summary
